*   Explain how the epigenome can change over time

### Epigenetics

Epigenetics refers to mitotically-heritable biological phenomena that regulate the activity of the genome without affecting the underlying DNA sequence.

In other words, epigenetics refers to chemical modifications that provide a layer of information that works in combination with the base layer (the genome) to regulate gene function. This epigenetic information allows the DNA sequence of the genome (which is largely the same in every cell of an individual’s body) to perform differently in different contexts – switching genes on or off accordingly. 

Epigenetics achieves this without altering the DNA sequence in which our genes are encoded; instead it provides instructions for how the DNA should be interpreted. A crucial detail is that, to qualify as ‘epigenetic’, the epigenetic layer must be mitotically-heritable, i.e. it must be able to survive cell division (mitosis) and therefore have the potential to be replicated across generations of cells over time. This feature means that epigenetic information has the ability to have long-lasting influences on gene expression and subsequent functional effects on characteristics, health and disease.

The following video introduces the concept of epigenetics. It discusses what we mean by epigenetics, some classic examples of epigenetics in other species, and why epigenetics might be interesting to epidemiologists.

Even if you have a background in molecular biology, we recommend that you watch this introductory video so that you're aware of the definition of epigenetics we'll be using in the rest of this course.

![](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMQVDNLhQn0&t=175s)

