### What is an EWAS?

Epigenome-wide association studies (EWAS) are the most commonly used analysis approach in epigenetic epidemiology. EWAS involve statistical tests being applied to each feature in a ‘genome-wide’ epigenetic dataset to assess the association between epigenetic features and a variable of interest. The term is most commonly used to describe studies of array-based (or increasingly, sequencing-based) DNA methylation datasets.

Watch the video below to learn more about EWAS and the key steps involved in running them.

![](https://youtu.be/r439YI7VcbI)


### EWAS study design and limitations

EWAS study design considerations and limitations outlined in the Introduction to Epigenetic Epidemiology video from week 1. Review that video now if you need to.

#### Study design

In principle, any study design used in epidemiology can be used to conduct an EWAS. 

![The following figure is taken from Epigenome-Wide Association Studies for Common Human Diseases by Rakyan et al., Nature Reviews Genetics, 2011](https://media.springernature.com/lw685/springer-static/image/art%3A10.1038%2Fnrg3000/MediaObjects/41576_2011_Article_BFnrg3000_Fig1_HTML.jpg)

#### Challenges in epigenetic epidemiology: similarities with genetic epidemiology

The EWAS was borne from the GWAS, but fundamental differences between genetic and epigenetic measurements mean that approaches applied in genetic epidemiology cannot be simply applied to epigenetic epidemiology and their results interpreted in the same way.

```{r epigenetics3, echo=FALSE}
quiz(  
question("'Which of the following challenges apply to BOTH epigenetic AND genetic epidemiology? (select all that apply)",
    answer("Tissue specificity", correct = FALSE),
    answer("DNA quality", correct = TRUE),
    answer("Adequate sample size", correct = TRUE),
    answer("Multiple testing", correct = TRUE),
    answer("Reverse causation",correct = FALSE),
    answer("Studies usually conducted on people of white European ancestry", correct = TRUE),
    incorrect = "Try again, at least some of your selections are wrong.",
    correct = "Correct!\n\nDNA quality, whether the sample size provides adequate sample size, and issues with multiple testing are issues that affect both genetic and epigenetic epidemiology. Both fields also suffer from a focus on samples largely comprised of people of white European ancestry, with a limited understanding of whether findings are generalisable to people with different ancestries.\n\nIssues of tissue specificity and reverse causation tend not to affect genetic studies.", 
    allow_retry=TRUE,random_answer_order = TRUE)
)
```

#### Specific challenges in epigenetic epidemiology

The epigenome is a complex phenotypic trait, therefore there are specific challenges to the design, conduct and interpretation of epigenetic studies that are important to consider. Some of these are discussed in the Introduction to Epigenetic Epidemiology video from week 1:

*   Confounding and reverse causation   
*   Technical confounding 
*   Tissue specificity
*   Cellular heterogeneity
*   Confounding by genetics

The degree to which it is necessary to mitigate some of these challenges will depend largely on whether the research aims to identify causal associations (i.e. causal effects of exposures on epigenetics, and epigenetics as a causal determinant of disease) or correlated epigenetic markers to indicate past exposure or predict future disease (where causality is not important).

### Practical: interpreting EWAS results

In this practical, you are going to view and interpret results from an EWAS. You will learn how to:

*   Find the number of associations that surpass a P-value threshold
*   Interpret QQ and Manhattan plots of EWAS results
*   Draw a volcano plot of EWAS results
*   Look up gene functions for top hits

We are using methylation and phenotype data from this paper: 

[Tsaprouni et al. (2014) Cigarette smoking reduces DNA methylation levels at multiple genomic loci but the effect is partially reversible upon cessation. Epigenetics. 9(10):1382-96.](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25424692)

This study used the 450k array to compare blood DNA methylation in smokers and non-smokers.

The following EWAS model has been run: 

*   DNA methylation ~ Smoking status + + CD4T cells + CD8T cells + B cells + NK cells + Granulocytes + Monocytes + bisulfite conversion batch

#### Load the EWAS results

As discussed in the Introduction to EWAS video, EWAS results tables commonly comprise:

*   Epigenetic feature identifiers (e.g. CpG IDs on Illumina arrays are in the format of a unique number prefixed by ‘cg’) 
*   Regression coefficients (effect estimates)
*   Coefficent standard errors
*   P-values 
*   P-values adjusted for multiple testing
*   Information about each CpG (e.g. chromosome, genomic coordinate, nearest gene, relation to CpG island)

#### Adjust for multiple testing and summarise the number of "hits"

We'll start by loading the EWAS results and taking a look at the first few rows:

```{r load_summary_stats, exercise=TRUE}

res <- read.csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/2spcfydm8tyz2oz/model2.csv?dl=1",header=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

head(res)

dim(res)

```

*Note that there are only 45,759 CpGs in this EWAS results file, rather than 450k+. This is to limit loading times for the purposes of this practical!*

Next, we'll calculate how many CpG sites show what looks like robust association with smoking, i.e. the number of CpGs surpassing a P-value threshold. *Remember the importance of adjusting for multiple testing*.

You'll see that we have most of the information we need in the results files, but we're missing P-values after adjustment for multiple testing, so let's generate those. We can generate both the FDR-adjusted p-value and the Bonferroni-adjusted p-value:

```{r adjust_MT, exercise=TRUE}

res$fdr_p <- p.adjust(res$p, method="fdr")
res$bonf_p <- p.adjust(res$p, method="bonferroni")

head(res)

```

Calculate the number of CpGs that surpass an unadjusted P-value of 0.05:
```{r P_005, exercise=TRUE}
length(res$p[res$p<0.05])
```

Now adjust the above code yourself to calculate the number of CpGs that surpass the 0.05 threshold AFTER adjustment for multiple testing, using both the Bonferroni and the FDR method:

```{r MT_005, exercise=TRUE}

# First run these lines again
res$fdr_p <- p.adjust(res$p, method="fdr")
res$bonf_p <- p.adjust(res$p, method="bonferroni")

# Then write your own code...



```


```{r epigenetics4, echo=FALSE}
quiz(
question_text("How many CpGs are associated with smoking with an FDR-adjusted P-value <0.05?",
    answer("1539", correct=T),
    allow_retry=TRUE),
question_text("How many CpGs are associated with smoking with a Bonferroni-adjusted P-value <0.05?",
    answer("129", correct=T),
    allow_retry=TRUE)
)
```

You can see that FDR-adjustment for multiple testing is less strict than Bonferroni-adjustment. 

#### Visualise results

**QQ plot**

We can use the R package `qqman` to draw QQ plots.

A quantile-quantile (QQ) plot shows the observed distribution of the p-values (y-axis) against the expected distribution of p-values under the null hypothesis of no association (y-axis). Deviations from the line suggest either true associations or spurious associations due to other factors. The inflation factor λ gives an estimate of systematic bias that needs to be corrected for. 

```{r QQ, exercise=TRUE}

library(qqman) # if you have not already installed qqman, you can do so using install.packages("qqman")

qq(res$p)

```

```{r epigenetics5, echo = FALSE}
quiz(
question(
  "The QQ plot shows...",
  answer("Substantial inflation of p-values", correct = TRUE),
  answer("No inflation of p-values", correct = FALSE),
  allow_retry = TRUE, correct = "Correct! The P-values are much smaller than would be expected given the null distribution. They come away from the null line very soon. This suggests either you've found many very robust associations... or substantial confounding at many CpGs."
))
```

**Manhattan plot**

We can use the R package `qqman` to draw Manhattan plots.

A Manhattan plot is a plot of -log10 p values (y-axis) against genomic location (x-axis). It allows us to quickly see if there are any loci that are associated with smoking, the size of the p value and the location on the genome. 

```{r Manhattan, exercise=TRUE}

library(qqman) # if you have not already installed qqman, you can do so using install.packages("qqman")

manhattan(x=res,
          p="p",
          chr="chromosome",
          bp="position",
          suggestiveline=-log10(max(res$p[p.adjust(res$p,method="fdr")<0.05])),
          genomewideline = -log10(max(res$p[p.adjust(res$p,method="bonferroni")<0.05]))
          )
```

```{r epigenetics6, echo = FALSE}
quiz(
question(
  "The blue line shows...",
  answer("The Bonferroni-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = FALSE),
  answer("The FDR-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = TRUE),
  allow_retry = TRUE,random_answer_order = TRUE),
question(
    "The red line shows...",
  answer("The Bonferroni-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = TRUE),
  answer("The FDR-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = FALSE),
  allow_retry = TRUE,random_answer_order = TRUE)
)
```

**Volcano plots**

While the Manhattan plot lets us see which CpG sites have small associated p-values, we can use volcano plots to view p-values and **effect sizes** on the same plot.

We can draw a volcano plot using the commonly-used R package for plotting data, `ggplot2`.

*If you are feeling confident with R, you could try to work out exactly what this code is doing, but don't worry if you do not feel confident doing this - generating plots is not an important part of this unit! You just need to be able to interpret them* 

```{r Volcano, exercise=TRUE}

# Load library
library(ggplot2)

# make note of the FDR and Bonferroni-adjusted P-value thresholds:
fdr_threshold <- -log10(max(res$p[p.adjust(res$p,method="fdr")<0.05]))
bonf_threshold <- -log10(max(res$p[p.adjust(res$p,method="bonferroni")<0.05]))

# create the plot
res_plot <- ggplot(data=res, aes(x=coefficient, y=-log10(p))) +
  	geom_point(alpha=0.5, size=1.75, aes(colour=abs(coefficient)>0.05 & p<fdr_threshold)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = fdr_threshold,colour="blue") +
    geom_hline(yintercept = bonf_threshold,colour="red") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = -0.05,linetype="dashed") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0.05,linetype="dashed") +
  	scale_colour_manual(values=c("black","red"))+
    theme_classic()+
  	theme(legend.position="none",plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))+
  	ggtitle("Methylation ~ Smoking")

res_plot

```

```{r epigenetics7, echo = FALSE}
quiz(
question(
  "The red points show CpGs that are associated with smoking...",
  answer("...with an FDR-adjusted P-value <0.05 and an effect size greater than 0.05 in either direction", correct = TRUE),
  answer("...with an FDR-adjusted P-value >0.05 and an effect size greater than 0.05 in either direction", correct = FALSE),
    answer("...with an unadjusted P-value <0.05 and an effect size greater than 0.05 in either direction", correct = FALSE),
  allow_retry = TRUE,random_answer_order = TRUE),
question(
    "The red line shows...",
  answer("The Bonferroni-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = TRUE),
  answer("The FDR-adjusted P-value threshold", correct = FALSE),
  allow_retry = TRUE,random_answer_order = TRUE)
)
```

What general pattern do you observe between p-value and effect size?

#### Look up CpGs and compare models

Finally, we will take a look at which CpGs are most strongly associated (FDR-adjusted P<0.05 and effect size >5% in either direction) with smoking according to this EWAS.

```{r GetHits, exercise=TRUE}

# Select CpGs with FDR-adjusted P<0.05 and effect size >5%
hits <- res[which(abs(res$coefficient)>0.05 & p.adjust(res$p,method="fdr")<0.05),]

# Order hits by p-value, so the CpGs with the smallest p-values are at the top
hits[order(hits$p),]
```

Look up some of these CpGs in the [EWAS catalog](http://www.ewascatalog.org) to see if they have been reported by any other EWAS. 

*   What traits have they previously been associated with? 
*   Google the gene name of the CpG third from the top of your list of hits. Can we be confident that the association with smoking at this CpG would replicate in an independent dataset?

