## 4. Extra material {.tabset}

### Extra material

The information in this section is designed to guide your further reading and provide extra context and information for those who are interested. You will not be expected to have read this information or completed any activities before any live session.

### Epigenetic inheritance

You will recall from video 1 that epigenetic factors are ‘heritable’. The word ‘heritable’ has its own definitional ambiguities that have compounded confusion around what epigenetics is. 

The intended meaning in this context is the faithful replication of epigenetic patterns from parent to daughter cells during cell division (mitosis and perhaps meiosis) associated with normal growth (e.g. skin cells dividing and replenishing). 

However, many have interpreted the term ‘heritable’ as referring to the passing of information between generations of individuals, from parent to child, introducing the idea that epigenetic variation acquired by a parent due to their life experiences may be transmitted to their offspring.

At this juncture, it is important to make clear the distinction between inter- and trans-generational epigenetic inheritance, which are terms often used interchangeably in the literature, but which are different phenomena. Both terms refer to the idea that epigenetic variation can be passed on to subsequent generations, but the proposed mechanism is quite different.

**Transgenerational epigenetic inheritance** refers to the passing of epigenetic variation from an exposed generation to one that was not exposed, as either an adult, a child, a fetus or even a germ cell within a developing embryo. Therefore, after an exposure, epigenetic variation must be traceable in the second generation (if the original exposed individual was male or a non-pregnant female) or third generation (if the original exposed individual was a pregnant female) to be considered truly “transgenerational”. The idea that transgenerational epigenetic inheritance might exist has captivated scientists, philosophers and the lay public alike. Some have argued that transgenerational epigenetic inheritance is Lamarckian – i.e. that it supports the idea (inaccurately named after 19th century French naturalist Jean-Baptiste Lamarck) that an individual can pass the characteristics acquired through their life on to their offspring, with a lasting impact on evolution. 

**Intergenerational epigenetic inheritance** refers to the passing of epigenetic variation from one generation to the next through direct exposure, either to the individual while they are in utero, or to the germ cells from which the individual was conceived. *There is no requirement for this effect to persist in future generations.*

![From: Heard & Martienssen, 2014 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2014.02.045](https://marlin-prod.literatumonline.com/cms/attachment/6d0f549e-eaf1-4fb7-bc79-a0fba08a2b69/gr1.jpg){width=400px}

There is a growing evidence linking maternal pregnancy exposures to variation in offspring DNA methylation, which supports the existence of intergenerational epigenetic effects (we will discuss this in more detail in the session on molecular epidemiological research in the IEU). 

In contrast, the existence of transgenerational epigenetic inheritance is a contentious topic. Although transgenerational epigenetic inheritance appears to be relatively common in plants and can occur in animals such as nematodes, there is little evidence to support it occurring in humans, or indeed, any other mammal ([Heard and Martienssen, 2014](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24679529/); [Perez and Lehner, 2019](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30602724/); [van Otterdijk and Michels, 2016](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27037350/)). The phenomenon would require that the epigenetic variation evades the normal rounds of epigenetic erasure that occur in the early embryo and its germ line, which, based on current understanding of these mechanisms, makes it somewhat unfeasible in species that rely on the germline for reproduction. 

Although some studies appear to show evidence of transgenerational epigenetic inheritance in rodents, there is disagreement over the interpretation and replicability of their findings. Where observational studies in humans have found associations between an exposure in one generation and health outcomes in subsequent generations, transgenerational epigenetic inheritance has sometimes been suggested as the most plausible underlying mechanism. However, in addition to being open to confounding and other sources of bias, very few of these studies have actually explored, or indeed had the necessary data or biological samples to explore, epigenetic mechanisms. Those with epigenetic data (for example studies of offspring of parents exposed to the Dutch Hunger Winter led by Bas Heijmans at the University of Leiden) have so far only been able to demonstrate evidence suggesting intergenerational epigenetic inheritance – i.e. associations with epigenetic variation in offspring who were exposed in utero, either directly as a fetus or as a germ cell during their parent’s fetal development.

### Replication and validation

#### Replication

To minimise the chance of reporting false positives (spurious findings), researchers often attempt to replicate their EWAS findings **using the same approach and technology in an independent dataset**. Associations in the same direction and of a similar magnitude can help to strengthen confidence in findings.

Replicating findings often requires collaboration between different research groups. Several consortia have been established to facilitate collaboration between studies with comparable data. Consortia can coordinate meta-analysis of EWAS summary statistics across multiple independent studies, thus boosting sample size and power to detect smaller effects.

For example, the Pregnancy and Childhood Epigenetics (PACE) consortium [Felix et al. 2018](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29025028/) was set up to help coordinate multicohort studies of epigenetic data in relation to maternal (and paternal) exposures during pregnancy and exposures and outcomes in childhood.

![](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/319760990/figure/fig2/AS:603029296402433@1520784796141/Current-main-exposures-outcomes-and-methodological-topics-in-the-PACE-Consortium.png)

Here are some links to PACE consortium papers:

* [DNA Methylation in Newborns and Maternal Smoking in Pregnancy: Genome-wide Consortium Meta-analysis](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27040690/)
* [Maternal BMI at the start of pregnancy and offspring epigenome-wide DNA methylation: findings from the pregnancy and childhood epigenetics (PACE) consortium](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29016858/)
* [Maternal alcohol consumption and offspring DNA methylation: findings from six general population-based birth cohorts](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29172695/)
* [Meta-analysis of epigenome-wide association studies in neonates reveals widespread differential DNA methylation associated with birthweight](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31015461/)
* [Epigenome-wide meta-analysis of blood DNA methylation in newborns and children identifies numerous loci related to gestational age](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32114984/)
* [Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy and DNA Methylation in Newborns](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31230546/)
* [Maternal Gestational Diabetes Mellitus and Newborn DNA Methylation: Findings From the Pregnancy and Childhood Epigenetics Consortium](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31601636/)
* [Maternal anxiety during pregnancy and newborn epigenome-wide DNA methylation](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33414500/)

#### Validation

To mitigate the effects of measurement error in methylation data, technical validation is performed on the same samples but using a different technology.

The following figure shows various methods for measuring DNA methylation, which could be used to validate findings from an Illumina array. Ideally, validation methods should belong to a different category from the original method. In practice though, findings from the Illumina array are usually validated using pyrosequencing, which is also a bisulfite-based strategy. 

![Olkhov-Mitsel E, Bapat B. Cancer Med. 2012 Oct;1(2):237-60](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ekaterina_Olkhov-Mitsel/publication/235364625/figure/fig6/AS:282625580257284@1444394597212/Main-strategies-for-DNA-methylation-analysis-classified-into-three-categories.png)

### Practical: epigenetic age acceleration

If you have time and are interested, you may want to complete this practical activity.

It will help you learn/improve your R skills and enables you to explore a variable derived from epigenetic data: age acceleration.

Thanks and credit for the original design of this practical goes to Paul Yousefi and Andrew Simpkin.

#### By the end of this practical, you will be able to...

a.	Draw a scatterplot to compare DNA methylation age with actual age
b.	Estimate the correlation between DNA methylation age and actual age
c.	Perform linear regression to obtain age acceleration residuals
d.	Assess whether smoking is related to age acceleration

#### Introduction
We begin this practical having used the online calculator/predictor of DNA methylation age (freely available [here](http://dnamage.genetics.ucla.edu)) to predict methylation age for individuals who took part in this study:

*[Tsaprouni et al. (2014) Cigarette smoking reduces DNA methylation levels at multiple genomic loci but the effect is partially reversible upon cessation. Epigenetics. 9(10):1382-96](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25424692)*

There are two sets of data you'll need for this practical, `traits` and `pred.ages`. Both have been pre-loaded in this workbook, but if you want to explore the data outside of this tutorial, they are stored in a Dropbox folder [here](https://www.dropbox.com/sh/d76shp9yfya8uvp/AADb245inIdByBTd28H9uiXma?dl=0) (note that `pred.ages` is stored as a file called `methylation_ages.csv`).

*    `traits` is a data frame of phenotype data for each sample. The first column (`SampleID`) uniquely identifies each sample.
*    `pred.ages` is a column of DNA methylation predicted ages for the same individuals as have data in the traits data frame.

In this practical we will open the result from the online calculator, compare the predicted DNA methylation ages with the actual age for each individual using a scatterplot and estimate the correlation between the predicted and actual age. In part 2, we use linear regression to obtain age acceleration residuals (these tell us whether individuals are ahead or behind their epigenetic clock) for each individual and then test whether smoking is related to age acceleration.

#### Loading and exploring the data

You should be able to run this practical within this tutorial. Alternatively, you can open R on your computer and type the code directly into the console.

We will now load the results from the online calculator and the data containing the traits of the individuals. Both of these are saved in comma separated files, or csv files. These can be opened and viewed in Excel but also read straight into R using the read.csv() function. 

