#### Calculating age acceleration and relating it to smoking

Although the DNA methylation predicted ages are close to the actual ages in this sample, there are some individuals who are either younger or older than what was predicted. The idea of being ahead or behind your epigenetic clock has been called age acceleration. This is measured for each individual by getting the residuals (differences between the points and the fitted line) from a linear regression of DNA methylation age on actual age.

To carry out a linear regression in R, we use the lm() function.

```{r first_model, exercise=TRUE, exercise.lines = 5}
lm(DNAmAge ~ age, data=data.merged)
```

This just displays the result. We need to save those results into a new object (that we'll call `model`). Use the `names()` function to see what `model` contains:
```{r explore_model, exercise=TRUE, exercise.lines = 5}
model <- lm(DNAmAge ~ age, data=data.merged)


```

The object model now contains all the results from the linear regression of DNA methylation age on actual age. The residuals from this model tell us whether a person’s predicted age is younger than their actual age (negative residual) or older than their actual age (positive residual). The residuals are stored as `model$residuals`. We can store the residuals under a new variable, which we can join to our main dataset using the top three lines below. Use `head()` to check that this has worked. Then use `summary()` to summarise the age acceleration residuals.
```{r merge_residuals, exercise=TRUE, exercise.lines = 5}
model <- lm(DNAmAge ~ age, data=data.merged)
age.accel 	<- model$residuals
data.merged <- cbind(data.merged, age.accel)

```

Age acceleration (being biologically older than expected) and deceleration (being biologically younger than expected) has been linked to a wide variety of exposures and health outcomes. Let's see if it is related to smoking - i.e. do smokers tend to be biologically older/younger than non-smokers?

First, calculate age acceleration and add it to your data set (as above). Then add the code to conduct a linear regression of age acceleration on smoking using the `lm()` function. Store the model results as `model_smoking` and then use `summary(model_smoking)` to see all the key information. Use `confint()` to calculate the 95% confidence interval around your regression estimates.
```{r smoking_model, exercise=TRUE, exercise.lines = 5}
model <- lm(DNAmAge ~ age, data=data.merged)
age.accel 	<- model$residuals
data.merged <- cbind(data.merged, age.accel)


```

